page.title: 10 Wildlife around Torpoint
page.content: Our area offers many different kinds of habitat and is a haven for birds on migration.Many waders breed in Siberia and return to us in the winter.Others breed here and go south for the winter.In most years there are even some American birds blown off course over the Atlantic in the gales, such as the Spoonbill which has wintered at Whacker for several years running. Some insects also cross the Atlantic . The American Monarch butterfly is seen here in Autumn, and the first Red Admiral has flown across the channel from France.The anceint Oakwood of our area are very important as one Oak tree can support as many as 120 different kind of insects. There are many varieties of plants growing here some of them are very rare and only found in this country.
